==Características==
:''Artigo Principal: [[en/Lista de novos recursos]]''

Enquanto o jogo é modelado após o original, o [http://www.openttd.org/ OpenTTD] tem muitas características adicionais que melhoram radicalmente a jogabilidade. O OpenTTD tem gráficos costumizáveis, e o trabalho está em andamento para substituir gráficos TTD completamente. Muitos recursos foram inspirados por [http://www.ttdpatch.net/ TTDPatch], o popular realce para TTD, enquanto que outras características são orginais. OpenTTD é muito mais personalizável do que Trasnport Tycoon Deluxe através do uso de [[en/Archive/Manual/Settings/Advanced Settings]] e [[en/Manual/NewGRF|custom graphics]].

As melhorias mais significativas incluem a introdução do [[en/Manual/Multiplayer]], faixas ferroviárias construídas com a ferramenta [[en/Archive/Manual/Autorail]] e a ferramenta [[en/Construção em encostas|em encostas]], [[en/Manual/Waypoints]], trens que são [[en/Trens gigantescos|gigantescos]] com [[en/Archive/Manual/Multiheaded trains|mais motores]] maior e mas mapas mais realistas. Os jogadores mais avançados podem aproveitar [[en/Manual/Signals]] para obter mais controle sobre as estações e cruzamentos, um aumento no número de veículos autorizados, e  [[en/Estações não uniformes|mais flexíveis]] qunado se trata de estações.

Para tornar o jogo mais agradável, [[en/Archive/Manual/Yet Another PBS Patch|novos desbravadores trens]] foram adicionados para permitir que os trens encontrar o seu caminho melhor, um [[en/Manual/Convert rail|conversor ferroviário]] ferramenta para fazer a atualização mais fácil e uma [[en/Archive/Manual/Settings/Extra dynamite|ferramenta de dinamite maior]] para fazer as coisas explodindo muito mais rápido.

Há muitos mais recursos que estão presentes no OpenTTD e muito mais são adicionados todo o tempo. Para obter uma lista completa dos novos recursos, vá para a [[en/Lista de novos recursos]].

==História do Transport Tycoon==
O primeiro jogo Transport Tycoon (TT) foi lançado em 1994. Ele foi desenvolvido por [http://www.chrissawyer.com/ Chris Sawyer] e lançado por MicroProse. 
Era muito popular na época. Comparado com muitos outros jogos da época, foi espetacular. A jogabilidade intuitiva e os coloridos, gráficos nítidos, combinado com infinitas possibilidades para construir e moldar a rede ferroviária de seus sonhos tornaram um vencedor.
Com o lançamento do Transport Tycoon Deluxe (TTD) em 1995, the game was greatly improved. Many new features, including 4 different environments, maglev trains, one-way signals, etc, were implemented.
TTD continued to be played for many years after by a small, but fanatic bunch of gamers. Even though the game had been fairly successful, no direct sequel was announced. Chris Sawyer's Locomotion can be considered as successor, but could not connect to the previous success.

===The rise of TTDPatch===
Somewhere around 1996-1997, Josef Drexler started a project called [http://www.ttdpatch.net/ TTDPatch], which was (as the name implies) a patch for TTD. Originally it only did small things, but later on it was able to support [[en/Manual/NewGRF]] files, two company colours, and even trams. It fixes some problems with the game and also adds a lot of new features to it. The TTDPatch project has endured for many years and has changed the game quite radically.

===A Windows version===
A great problem during 1996 was that TTD had been written in assembly language and was not especially portable. Nevertheless, a Windows 95 conversion was made by FISH Technology Group in 1996, but it was only released by Microprose (later Hasbro Interactive) in 1999, in a Tycoon compilation known as "The Tycoon Collection", including Railroad Tycoon 2, Rollercoaster Tycoon, and Transport Tycoon Deluxe. This Windows version introduced a few bugs, including broken tutorials, and had a FISH UK logo added to the startup screens (removed from OpenTTD).

===Enter OpenTTD===
''The Patch's'' method of modifying the game made a lot of potential features near-impossible. [[en/Archive/Community/Users/Ludde]] contacted [http://www.tt-forums.net/ Owen Rudge] in 2003, and explained he was going to reverse engineer the game and convert TTD to [https://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/C (programming language) C]. A year later Ludde surprisingly presented Owen Rudge with the first [https://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_release release]. Forums were created where people discussed the new incarnation of the game. Response was positive, and other developers joined Ludde in the project. Work continues on OpenTTD to this day.

===OpenTTD 1.0.0===
At the end of 2009 an important milestone was reached. Up till this time graphics and sound files from Transport Tycoon Deluxe were required to play OpenTTD but now free and open alternatives, [[en/Archive/Community/OpenGFX Readme]] and [[en/Archive/Community/Sound Effects Replacement]], are also available and supported. These large community contributions made OpenTTD a fully stand-alone game for the first time and to mark this occasion this release was given the version number 1.0.0.

